[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] A settings object is an environment that provides additional information when JavaScript code is running.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] This includes the realm and module map, as well as HTML specific information such as the origin.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] The incumbent settings object is tracked in order to ensure that the browser knows which one to use for a given piece of user code.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] To better picture this, we can take a closer look at how the realm might be an issue.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] A **realm** can be roughly thought of as the global object.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] What is unique about realms is that they hold all of the necessary information to run JavaScript code.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] This includes objects like `Array` and `Error`.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] Each settings object has its own "copy" of these and they are not shared.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] That can cause some unexpected behavior in relation to promises.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] In order to get around this, we track something called the **incumbent settings object**.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] This represents information specific to the context of the user code responsible for a certain function call.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] To illustrate this a bit further we can take a look at how an `<iframe>` embedded in a document communicates with its host.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] In the above example, the inner text of the `<iframe>` will be updated only if the incumbent settings object is tracked.
[src:ioredis-client/global-objects-promise] This is because without tracking the incumbent, we may end up using the wrong environment to send the message.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:ioredis-client/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:ioredis-client/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] A robust, performance-focused and full-featured Redis client for Node.js.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis is a stable project and maintenance is done on a best-effort basis for relevant issues (contributions to ioredis will still be evaluated, reviewed, and merged when they benefit the project).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis is a robust, full-featured Redis client that is used in the world's biggest online commerce company Alibaba and many other awesome companies.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It works with Node callbacks and Native promises.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Transformation of command arguments and replies.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Abstraction for Lua scripting, allowing you to define custom commands.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Supports offline queue and ready checking.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Supports ES6 types, such as `Map` and `Set`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Refer to CHANGELOG.md for features and bug fixes introduced in v5.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] See the `examples/` folder for more examples.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When a new `Redis` instance is created, a connection to Redis will be created at the same time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] See API Documentation for all available options.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis provides several commands for developers to implement the Publish–subscribe pattern.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] There are two roles in this pattern: publisher and subscriber.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Publishers are not programmed to send their messages to specific subscribers.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Rather, published messages are characterized into channels, without knowledge of what (if any) subscribers there may be.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] By leveraging Node.js's built-in events module, ioredis makes pub/sub very straightforward to use.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Below is a simple example that consists of two files, one is publisher.js that publishes messages to a channel, the other is subscriber.js that listens for messages on specific channels.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It's worth noticing that a connection (aka a `Redis` instance) can't play both roles at the same time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] More specifically, when a client issues `subscribe()` or `psubscribe()`, it enters the "subscriber" mode.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] From that point, only commands that modify the subscription set are valid.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Namely, they are: `subscribe`, `psubscribe`, `unsubscribe`, `punsubscribe`, `ping`, and `quit`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When the subscription set is empty (via `unsubscribe`/`punsubscribe`), the connection is put back into the regular mode.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis v5 introduces a new data type called streams.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It doubles as a communication channel for building streaming architectures and as a log-like data structure for persisting data.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] With ioredis, the usage can be pretty straightforward.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis can set a timeout to expire your key, after the timeout has expired the key will be automatically deleted.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Every command that returns a bulk string has a variant command with a `Buffer` suffix.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It's worth noticing that you don't need the `Buffer` suffix variant in order to **send** binary data.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] If you want to send a batch of commands (e.g. > 5), you can use pipelining to queue the commands in memory and then send them to Redis all at once.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This way the performance improves by 50%~300% (See benchmark section).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] `redis.pipeline()` creates a `Pipeline` instance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] You can call any Redis commands on it just like the `Redis` instance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Most of the time, the transaction commands `multi` & `exec` are used together with pipeline.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis supports all of the scripting commands such as `EVAL`, `EVALSHA` and `SCRIPT`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] You can refer to the example for how to declare your custom commands.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This feature allows you to specify a string that will automatically be prepended to all the keys in a command, which makes it easier to manage your key namespaces.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Most Redis commands take one or more Strings as arguments, and replies are sent back as a single String or an Array of Strings.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] However, sometimes you may want something different.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] For instance, it would be more convenient if the `HGETALL` command returns a hash (e.g.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] `{ key: val1, key2: v2 }`) rather than an array of key values (e.g.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis has a flexible system for transforming arguments and replies.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] There are three built-in transformers, two argument transformers for `hmset` & `mset` and a reply transformer for `hgetall`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis supports the MONITOR command, which lets you see all commands received by the Redis server across all client connections, including from other client libraries and other computers.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The `monitor` method returns a monitor instance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] After you send the MONITOR command, no other commands are valid on that connection. ioredis will emit a monitor event for every new monitor message that comes across.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The callback for the monitor event takes a timestamp from the Redis server and an array of command arguments.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis 2.8 added the `SCAN` command to incrementally iterate through the keys in the database.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It's different from `KEYS` in that `SCAN` only returns a small number of elements each call, so it can be used in production without the downside of blocking the server for a long time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] However, it requires recording the cursor on the client side each time the `SCAN` command is called in order to iterate through all the keys correctly.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Since it's a relatively common use case, ioredis provides a streaming interface for the `SCAN` command to make things much easier.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Just like other commands, `scanStream` has a binary version `scanBufferStream`, which returns an array of buffers.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It's useful when the key names are not utf8 strings.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] There are also `hscanStream`, `zscanStream` and `sscanStream` to iterate through elements in a hash, zset and set.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The `hscanStream` also accepts the `noValues` option to specify whether Redis should return only the keys in the hash table without their corresponding values.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] You can learn more from the Redis documentation.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] By default, ioredis will try to reconnect when the connection to Redis is lost except when the connection is closed manually by `redis.disconnect()` or `redis.quit()`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] `retryStrategy` is a function that will be called when the connection is lost.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The argument `times` means this is the nth reconnection being made and the return value represents how long (in ms) to wait to reconnect.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When the return value isn't a number, ioredis will stop trying to reconnect, and the connection will be lost forever if the user doesn't call `redis.connect()` manually.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When reconnected, the client will auto subscribe to channels that the previous connection subscribed to.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This behavior can be disabled by setting the `autoResubscribe` option to `false`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] And if the previous connection has some unfulfilled commands (most likely blocking commands such as `brpop` and `blpop`), the client will resend them when reconnected.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This behavior can be disabled by setting the `autoResendUnfulfilledCommands` option to `false`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] By default, all pending commands will be flushed with an error every 20 retry attempts.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] That makes sure commands won't wait forever when the connection is down.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Set maxRetriesPerRequest to `null` to disable this behavior, and every command will wait forever until the connection is alive again (which is the default behavior before ioredis v4).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis can apply a client-side timeout to blocking commands (such as `blpop`, `brpop`, `bzpopmin`, `bzmpop`, `blmpop`, `xread`, `xreadgroup`, etc.).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This protects against scenarios where the TCP connection becomes a zombie (e.g., due to a silent network failure like a Docker network disconnect) and Redis never replies.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It is **disabled by default** and is only enabled when `blockingTimeout` is set to a positive number of milliseconds.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] If `blockingTimeout` is omitted, `0`, or negative (for example `-1`), ioredis does not arm any client-side timeouts for blocking commands and their behavior matches Redis exactly.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Besides auto-reconnect when the connection is closed, ioredis supports reconnecting on certain Redis errors using the `reconnectOnError` option.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This feature is useful when using Amazon ElastiCache instances with Auto-failover disabled.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] On these instances, test your `reconnectOnError` handler by manually promoting the replica node to the primary role using the AWS console.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The following writes fail with the error `READONLY`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Using `reconnectOnError`, we can force the connection to reconnect on this error in order to connect to the new master.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Furthermore, if the `reconnectOnError` returns `2`, ioredis will resend the failed command after reconnecting.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] On ElastiCache instances with Auto-failover enabled, `reconnectOnError` does not execute.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Instead of returning a Redis error, AWS closes all connections to the master endpoint until the new primary node is ready. ioredis reconnects via `retryStrategy` instead of `reconnectOnError` after about a minute.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] On ElastiCache instances with Auto-failover enabled, test failover events with the `Failover primary` option in the AWS console.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The Redis instance will emit some events about the state of the connection to the Redis server.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] You can also check out the `Redis#status` property to get the current connection status.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis publishes telemetry through Node.js `diagnostics_channel`, allowing APM tools and custom instrumentation to observe commands, connections, and batch operations without modifying application code.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] These channels use `TracingChannel#tracePromise()` and emit `start`, `end`, `asyncStart`, `asyncEnd`, and `error` sub-events.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Requires Node.js >= 18.19.0; on older versions the channels are silently unavailable (zero overhead).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Command arguments are sanitized before emission using rules adapted from `@opentelemetry/redis-common`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Sensitive values (e.g. values in `SET`, `AUTH` passwords) are replaced with `?`, while read-only commands like `GET` and `DEL` retain all arguments.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] This is safe by default: unlisted or custom commands have all arguments redacted.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Context types (`CommandTraceContext`, `BatchOperationContext`, `ConnectTraceContext`) are exported from `ioredis`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When a command can't be processed by Redis (being sent before the `ready` event), by default, it's added to the offline queue and will be executed when it can be processed.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Redis doesn't support TLS natively, however if the redis server you want to connect to is hosted behind a TLS proxy (e.g. stunnel) or is offered by a PaaS service that supports TLS connection (e.g.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Alternatively, specify the connection through a `rediss://` URL.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] To make it easier to configure we provide a few pre-configured TLS profiles that can be specified by setting the `tls` option to the profile's name or specifying a `tls.profile` option in case you need to customize some values of the profile.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis supports Sentinel out of the box.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It works transparently as all features that work when you connect to a single node also work when you connect to a sentinel group.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Make sure to run Redis >= 2.8.12 if you want to use this feature.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] ioredis **guarantees** that the node you connected to is always a master even after a failover.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] When a failover happens, instead of trying to reconnect to the failed node (which will be demoted to slave when it's available again), ioredis will ask sentinels for the new master node and connect to it.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] All commands sent during the failover are queued and will be executed when the new connection is established so that none of the commands will be lost.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] It's possible to connect to a slave instead of a master by specifying the option `role` with the value of `slave` and ioredis will try to connect to a random slave of the specified master, with the guarantee that the connected node is always a slave.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] If the current node is promoted to master due to a failover, ioredis will disconnect from it and ask the sentinels for another slave node to connect to.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] If you specify the option `preferredSlaves` along with `role: 'slave'` ioredis will attempt to use this value when selecting the slave from the pool of available slaves.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] The value of `preferredSlaves` should either be a function that accepts an array of available slaves and returns a single result, or an array of slave values priorities by the lowest `prio` value first with a default value of `1`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] Besides the `retryStrategy` option, there's also a `sentinelRetryStrategy` in Sentinel mode which will be invoked when all the sentinel nodes are unreachable during connecting.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p01] If `sentinelRetryStrategy` returns a valid delay time, ioredis will try to reconnect from scratch.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Redis Cluster provides a way to run a Redis installation where data is automatically sharded across multiple Redis nodes.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] A typical redis cluster contains three or more masters and several slaves for each master.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] It's possible to scale out redis cluster by sending read queries to slaves and write queries to masters by setting the `scaleReads` option.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] `scaleReads` is "master" by default, which means ioredis will never send any queries to slaves.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] "slave": Send write queries to masters and read queries to slaves.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] 3. a custom `function(nodes, command): node`: Will choose the custom function to select to which node to send read queries (write queries keep being sent to master).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] The first node in `nodes` is always the master serving the relevant slots.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] If the function returns an array of nodes, a random node of that list will be selected.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Every command will be sent to exactly one node.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] `GET`, `SET` and `HGETALL`), ioredis sends them to the node that serving the keys, and for other commands not containing keys, (e.g.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] `INFO`, `KEYS` and `FLUSHDB`), ioredis sends them to a random node.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Sometimes you may want to send a command to multiple nodes (masters or slaves) of the cluster, you can get the nodes via `Cluster#nodes()` method.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] `Cluster#nodes()` accepts a parameter role, which can be "master", "slave" and "all" (default), and returns an array of `Redis` instance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Sometimes the cluster is hosted within a internal network that can only be accessed via a NAT (Network Address Translation) instance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] See Accessing ElastiCache from outside AWS as an example.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This option is also useful when the cluster is running inside a Docker container.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Also it works for Clusters in cloud infrastructure where cluster nodes connected through dedicated subnet.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Specifying through may be useful if you don't know concrete internal host and know only node port.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Almost all features that are supported by `Redis` are also supported by `Redis.Cluster`, e.g. custom commands, transaction and pipeline.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] You can't use `multi` without pipeline (aka `cluster.multi({ pipeline: false })`).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This is because when you call `cluster.multi({ pipeline: false })`, ioredis doesn't know which node the `multi` command should be sent to.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] All commands executed successfully are readonly commands.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This makes sure that resending the pipeline won't have side effects.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Pub/Sub in cluster mode works exactly as the same as in standalone mode.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Internally, when a node of the cluster receives a message, it will broadcast the message to the other nodes. ioredis makes sure that each message will only be received once by strictly subscribing one node at the same time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] For sharded Pub/Sub, use the `spublish` and `ssubscribe` commands instead of the traditional `publish` and `subscribe`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] With the old commands, the Redis cluster handles message propagation behind the scenes, allowing you to publish or subscribe to any node without considering sharding.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] However, this approach has scalability limitations that are addressed with sharded Pub/Sub.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] All channel names that you pass to a single `ssubscribe` need to map to the same hash slot.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] You can call `ssubscribe` multiple times on the same cluster client instance to subscribe to channels across slots.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] The cluster's subscriber group takes care of forwarding the `ssubscribe` command to the shard that is responsible for the channels.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] AWS ElastiCache for Redis (Clustered Mode) supports TLS encryption.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] If you use this, you may encounter errors with invalid certificates.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] In standard mode, when you issue multiple commands, ioredis sends them to the server one by one.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] As described in Redis pipeline documentation, this is a suboptimal use of the network link, especially when such link is not very performant.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] The TCP and network overhead negatively affects performance.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Commands are stuck in the send queue until the previous ones are correctly delivered to the server.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This is a problem known as Head-Of-Line blocking (HOL).
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] ioredis supports a feature called “auto pipelining”.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] It can be enabled by setting the option `enableAutoPipelining` to `true`.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] In auto pipelining mode, all commands issued during an event loop are enqueued in a pipeline automatically managed by ioredis.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] At the end of the iteration, the pipeline is executed and thus all commands are sent to the server at the same time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This feature can dramatically improve throughput and avoids HOL blocking.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] In our benchmarks, the improvement was between 35% and 50%.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] While an automatic pipeline is executing, all new commands will be enqueued in a new pipeline which will be executed as soon as the previous finishes.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] When using Redis Cluster, one pipeline per node is created.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Commands are assigned to pipelines according to which node serves the slot.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] A pipeline will thus contain commands using different slots but that ultimately are assigned to the same node.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Note that the same slot limitation within a single command still holds, as it is a Redis limitation.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This sample code uses ioredis with automatic pipeline enabled.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] When Node receives requests, it schedules them to be processed in one or more iterations of the events loop.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] All commands issued by requests processing during one iteration of the loop will be wrapped in a pipeline automatically created by ioredis.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] When all events in the current loop have been processed, the pipeline is executed and thus all commands are sent to the server at the same time.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] While waiting for pipeline response from Redis, Node will still be able to process requests.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] All commands issued by request handler will be enqueued in a new automatically created pipeline.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This pipeline will not be sent to the server yet.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] As soon as a previous automatic pipeline has received all responses from the server, the new pipeline is immediately sent without waiting for the events loop iteration to finish.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This approach increases the utilization of the network link, reduces the TCP overhead and idle times and therefore improves throughput.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Here's some of the results of our tests for a single node.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] Each iteration of the test runs 1000 random commands on the server.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] By default, the error stack doesn't make any sense because the whole stack happens in the ioredis module itself, not in your code.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] So it's not easy to find out where the error happens in your code. ioredis provides an option `showFriendlyErrorStack` to solve the problem.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] This time the stack tells you that the error happens on the third line in your code.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] However, it would decrease the performance significantly to optimize the error stack.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] So by default, this option is disabled and can only be used for debugging purposes.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] You **shouldn't** use this feature in a production environment.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] `FLUSH ALL` will be invoked after each test, so make sure there's no valuable data in it before running tests.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] If your testing environment does not let you spin up a Redis server ioredis-mock is a drop-in replacement you can use in your tests.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] It aims to behave identically to ioredis connected to a Redis server so that your integration tests is easier to write and of better quality.
[src:ioredis-client/redis-ioredis-p02] I'm happy to receive bug reports, fixes, documentation enhancements, and any other improvements.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:ioredis-client/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
